    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-19T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-19T14:00:00-05:00" n="38"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d38">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/10113: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Weddell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-19T20:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 19, 1941—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 20—10:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>338. My 337, April 19, 6 p.m.<note n="2" xml:id="d38fn1">
                        <ref target="frus1941v02#pg_888">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                            888</ref>.</note> The failure of the Foreign Minister to clearly define
                    his Government’s policy as set forth in my telegram under reference, the tenor
                    of recent editorial comment as previously reported, the repercussion of news
                    from Greece, and the apparently general opinion of my American colleagues,
                    gained by a canvass, that important decisions concerning Spanish-Axis relations
                    will be shortly made and acted upon by this Government, make me feel that it
                    would be highly desirable that the various American Republics represented here
                    (within the limits of their declared policies in the present struggle against
                    aggression) make their views known to the Spanish Government especially to the
                    end that its neutrality be maintained. And this at the earliest moment.</p>
                <p>A military collapse in Greece or even a stalemate there would be controlling and
                    hastening factors designed for German-Spanish cooperation and action.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Weddell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
